The blue curve represents the real part of the wave

30
00:01:41,649 --> 00:01:45,257
function, while the red curve shows the imaginary part. Notice

31
00:01:45,357 --> 00:01:48,426
how they oscillate together, creating a complex wave.

32
00:01:48,516 --> 00:01:51,393
An important property of wave functions is that they

33
00:01:51,493 --> 00:01:54,541
must be normalized. This means the total probability of

34
00:01:54,641 --> 00:01:57,690
finding the particle somewhere in space must equal one.

35
00:01:59,783 --> 00:02:03,191
The wave function itself is not directly observable, but its

36
00:02:03,291 --> 00:02:06,699
square modulus gives us the probability density. This is one

37
00:02:06,799 --> 00:02:09,740
of the most important concepts in quantum mechanics.

38
00:02:09,833 --> 00:02:13,247
The probability density is defined as the absolute square of

39
00:02:13,347 --> 00:02:16,644
the wave function. Mathematically, we write it as psi star

40
00:02:16,744 --> 00:02:19,163
times psi, or the magnitude of psi squared.

